<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-822  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 822.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 24 1989 n535 p58(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber emerges for high-speed nets; variety of standards,fiber-optic technologies.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anbamalai, K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) 100M-bit-sectoken-ring local-area network (LAN) standard is finding use inapplications that demand high-speed and high-bandwidth, such asbackbone networks, mainframe-mainframe communications, complexgraphics, and linking several systems to a ring LAN throughconcentrators.andP;  The FDDI standard's physical medium dependent(PMD) sublayer has several requirements for optical interface andtransmission performance that impact FDDI hardware.andP;  These includeuse of surface- or edge-emitting light-emitting diodes for a -14to -20 dBm active output interface, use of PIN diodes orphotodiodes as photodectors, and the use of 1.3-micron silicafiber for low 0.35dB-km attenuation.andP;  Single-mode PMD technologyshould find acceptance in metropolitan-area networks, especiallywith the use of wavelength division multiplexing for improvingdata capacity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Token Ring NetworksApplicationsSpecificationsRequirements AnalysisOptical CommunicationsWide Area NetworksFiber Optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Summary of key specifications requirements of multimode PMD.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>